\section{Refinement workflow}

Because the forward model combines beam phase space, detector geometry, sample alignment,
mosaicity, and crystallographic intensity within a single image calculation, a fully global
refinement from arbitrary starting values would lead to strong correlations between
instrumental and sample-specific parameters. We therefore adopt a sequential refinement
strategy where each stage isolates a distinct source of
contrast in the measured image before the next class of parameters is introduced. Beam and
detector terms first establish the fixed experimental geometry shared across measurements.
Sample alignment and goniometer misalignment then determine how the sample is embedded in
that geometry and, in turn, where the reflections appear on the detector. With the reflection
positions established, mosaicity can be inferred from their broadening, and the remaining
intensity variation can then be attributed to ordered structure or disorder. The staged
workflow is summarized in Table~\ref{tab:refinement_workflow}.
