The first two stages isolate the instrumental contribution to the measured image. Direct-beam
images collected at several detector distances are fitted to determine the incident-beam widths
and divergences used in the forward model. These quantities define the baseline phase-space
spread of the incoming beam and therefore the instrumental broadening that would be present
even for an ideal sample. Detector distance, tilts, in-plane rotation, and beam center are
then refined from the hBN Debye--Scherrer rings. This calibration fixes the mapping from
reciprocal-space intersections to detector coordinates independently of the sample, so that
later discrepancies in peak position or line shape are not absorbed spuriously into sample
parameters.

With the instrumental terms fixed, refinement proceeds to the sample geometry. For each
sample image, alignment and goniometer misalignment are determined from indexed
Bragg-peak positions rather than from global intensities, because feature location is the most
direct signature of geometric error. Reflections spanning both the specular and off-specular
regions are included so that the fit is constrained simultaneously by the central
$Q_z$-dominated features and by the off-axis intersections of the reciprocal-space rings. This step refines and establishes the actual incidence
condition and illuminated geometry of the experiment, which must be known before peak
widths and intensities can be interpreted physically.

Mosaicity is refined only after the reflection positions have been fixed, so that the remaining
variation in line shape can be attributed to crystallite misorientation rather than to geometric
offset. Two images acquired at different $\theta_i$ are fitted jointly using local regions of
interest around indexed reflections. The shared mosaic kernel is therefore determined by peak shape rather than
by absolute counts. Using two incidence angles is important because the same mosaic
distribution is then sampled through different cuts of reciprocal space, which reduces
degeneracy between alignment and angular broadening. In this stage the specular and
off-specular regions play complementary roles: the off-specular arcs constrain the core width
of the distribution, whereas the persistence and decay of specular intensity constrain the tail
character more strongly. The refined mosaic parameters are reported as the Lorentzian full
width at half-maximum, $2\Gamma$, the Gaussian full width at half-maximum,
$2\sqrt{2\ln 2}\,\sigma$, and the mixing factor $\eta$.

Only after the geometric and mosaic terms have converged are the remaining intensity
variations assigned to sample structure. The full dark-subtracted 2D images, including the specular region, are used to refine an
overall scale together with the parameters entering the structure-factor intensity model,
including occupancies, anisotropic Debye--Waller factors, and symmetry-allowed static
displacements. At this point the relative Bragg intensities become interpretable as constraints
on the average ordered structure because the competing effects of beam shape, detector
geometry, sample alignment, and mosaic broadening have already been fixed. Disorder parameters are introduced only after convergence of the ordered model and are
refined with the ordered structure held fixed. This final separation is essential because the
diffuse intensity along $Q_z$ near and between the Bragg peaks is the signature most directly
associated with stacking disorder and is otherwise easily confounded with average-structure
or broadening effects. All detector images are dark-subtracted before fitting. 

